Final Exam - 175 Points¶

Case Study: Identifying and Exploring the Properties of Malignant Breast Tumors¶

In this analysis, we would like to build a classifier model that predicts whether a breast tumor is malignant or benign, based on it's tissue sample properties for new datasets. In addition, we would like to learn more about what tissue sample attribute properties (and attribute relationships) characterize malignant vs. benign breast tumor tissue samples.

The data in the breast_tumor_scaled.csv file contains a random sample of benign and malignant breast tumor tissue samples from 569 patients.

More Dataset Information¶

The following physical attributes are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image.

Interesting Factoid: Furthermore, each of these physical attributes have already been scaled, so they should all roughly have the same standard deviation and mean. Scaling variables before running a regularized regression first can help the results not be dominated just by variables that have much larger scale.

Specifically, the data in the breast_tumor_scaled.csv file contains the following attributes about these breast tumor tissue samples.

  • diagnosis - whether the tumor was malignant ('M') or benign ('B')
  • radius_mean
  • texture_mean
  • perimeter_mean
  • area_mean
  • smoothness_mean
  • compactness_mean
  • concavity_mean
  • concave points_mean
  • symmetry_mean
  • fractal dimension_mean

3. Inference¶

Next, we would like to determine if we have sufficient evidence to suggest that there is an association between breast tumor diagnosis and tissue sample smoothness_mean for ALL breast tumors.

We will do this by determining whether we have sufficient evidence to suggest that the average smoothness mean of ALL benign breast tumors is different from the average smoothness mean of ALL malignant breast tumors.

3.1. Hypotheses¶

Set up your hypotheses for this analysis. Make sure you define any parameters that you use.

Hypothesis: There is an association between breast tumor diagnosis and tissue sample smoothness_mean Alternative Hypothesis: There is not an association between breast tumor diagnosis and tissue sample smoothness_mean

3.2. Conditions¶

Check the conditions for conducting this hypothesis test.

The sample size is greater than 30 and the sample is randomly collected

In [ ]:
In [ ]:

3.3. Test Statistic¶

Calculate the test statistic for this hypothesis test.

In [26]:
df_benign = dfc[dfc['diagnosis'] == 'B'].reset_index(drop=True)
df_malignant = dfc[dfc['diagnosis'] == 'M'].reset_index(drop=True)
In [27]:
dfbm = df_benign['smoothness_mean'].mean()
dfbstd = df_benign['smoothness_mean'].std()
dfmm = df_malignant['smoothness_mean'].mean()
dfmstd = df_malignant['smoothness_mean'].std()
In [28]:
test_stat = ((dfbm-dfmm) - 0) / np.sqrt((dfbstd**2)/len(df_benign) + (dfmstd**2)/len(df_malignant))
test_stat
Out[28]:
-9.19494177347912

3.5. p-value¶

Calculate the p-value for this hyopthesis test.

In [29]:
pvalue = 2*(1-t.cdf(np.abs(test_stat), df=145))
pvalue
Out[29]:
4.440892098500626e-16

3.6. Conclusion¶

Use your p-value and a significance level of $\alpha=0.05$ to make a conclusion about your hypotheses.

Since the p-value is lower than the significance level, we reject the null hypothesis, which means there is sufficient evidence to suggest that there is an association between breast tumor diagnosis and tissue sample smoothness_mean for all breast tumors.

3.7. Conceptual Question - Decreasing Sample Size¶

What if everything from our previous analysis (statistics, calculations, etc.) had remained unchanged except our sample of benign tumors were to decrease. Would this change make it more or less likely for us to reject the null hypothesis? Explain.

More likely as the test_stat would increase, resulting in the p-value to increase

def plot_roc(fpr, tpr, auc, lw=2):
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=lw,
             label='ROC curve (area = '+str(round(auc,3))+')')

def plot_roc(fpr, tpr, auc, lw=2):
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=lw,
             label='ROC curve (area = '+str(round(auc,3))+')')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

4.6.1. Predictive Probability Threshold¶

Suppose that we would like for our classifier to correctly identify malignant tumors 100% of the time. Ideally, we would also like for our misclassification rate of benign tumors to be as low as it can possibly be, while still giving us 100% accuracy when identifying malignant tumors.

Using the logistic regression model that you selected from 4.5.1, select the predictive probability threshold that will best meet our classifier goals with respect to the test dataset.

Give the sensitivity and specificity of the test dataset classifications using this predictive probability threshold that you selected.

In [94]:
def tpr_fpr_thresh(y, pred_prob, thresh):
    yhat = 1*(pred_prob >= thresh)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true=y, y_pred=yhat).ravel()
    tpr = tp / (fn + tp)
    fpr = fp / (fp + tn)
    return pd.DataFrame({'threshold':[thresh],
                         'tpr':[tpr], 
                         'fpr':[fpr]})

5.2. Cross-Fold Validation¶

In order to help us determine which explanatory variables to include in our malignant tumor linear regression model that will yield good predictions for new datasets, we will try out the following four linear regression models.

  1. Non-Regularized Linear Regression
  2. LASSO Linear Regression with $\lambda=0.0025$
  3. LASSO Linear Regression with $\lambda=0.01$
  4. LASSO Linear Regression with $\lambda=10$

For each of these models we will use k=5 crossfold validation to evaluate the 5 test fold performance.

5.4. Reduced Model Inference¶

Let's conduct inference on the slopes in the reduced model from 5.3.2.

5.4.1. At Least One Population Slope being Non-Zero¶

First, we would like to determine if we have sufficient evidence to suggest if at least one of the corresponding population slopes in the reduced model is non-zero.

5.4.1.1. Hypotheses¶

Set up the hyptheses for this test.

Hypothesis: None of the corresponding population slopes in the reduced model is non-zero.
Alternative: At least one of the corresponding population slopes in the reduced model is non-zero.

6. Combinatorics and Probability¶

Suppose that a class of 100 students has 90 people that are right-handed and 10 people that are left-handed. What is the probability of randomly selecting a group of 5 students in which 2 are right-handed and 3 are left-handed.

Note: The order/way in which we selected the students in this sample does not matter.

Note: I'm not looking for a simulated approximation for this probability. You should calculate the THEORETICAL probability here.

In [108]:
import math
In [109]:
denom = math.factorial(100)/math.factorial(5)
In [110]:
rh = (90*89)/(2*1)
In [111]:
lh = (10*9*8)/(3*2*1)
In [112]:
num = rh*lh
In [114]:
theoretical = num/denom
theoretical
Out[114]:
6.179614133677192e-151
